hints_latex:
For $f(x)$ to be a probability density function on {[}a,b{]} it needs to
satisfy

\begin{align*}
(i) \quad f(x) \geq 0
\end{align*}

for all $x \in [a,b]$, and

\begin{align*}
(ii) \quad \int_a^b f(x)\,dx = 1.
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
The constant \emph{k} needs to be chosen such that \emph{f(x)}
integrates to 1:

\begin{align*}
\int_1^4 kx^{3/2}\,dx &= k\int_1^4x^{3/2}\,dx =k\frac25x^{5/2}\bigg|_1^4 \\
&=k\frac25(4^{5/2}-1^{5/2}) = k\frac{62}5,
\end{align*}

hence we choose \emph{k=5/62}.

statement_latex:
Let \emph{k} be a constant. Find the value of \emph{k} such that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(x) = k x^{3/2}
\end{align*}

is a probability density function on 1 $\leq$ \emph{x} $\leq$ 4.
